name: sfchronicle
text:
COVID-19 hospitalizations rose slightly in the Bay Area as local health departments recorded 693 patients as of August 14, an increase of 16 from the day before.

Hospitalizations across California fell slightly to 5,112 on Saturday, a decrease of 77.

https://t.co/OjY8oOL9WS

name: sfchronicle
text: “I did not feel safe at my job. I was concerned about endangering my family to COVID-19 through my exposure at work to personnel who were not strictly adhering to social distancing guidelines and the safety protocols I had written.” https://t.co/t5aEUPgCVa

name: sfchronicle
text: With the Bay Area’s most elite dining rooms closed, restaurants have been offering luxe, elaborate meals on nearby farms in the hope of staying in business. https://t.co/UZVh3XR34x

name: sfchronicle
text:
Free Joey.

@scottostler says it's time to spring Joey Bart from the Giants’ Alternate Site, or Area 51, or wherever it is he is being held captive. https://t.co/XRNyWHDAhi

name: sfchronicle
text:
Here's the report from the 49ers’ first practice of training camp, from @Eric_Branch. One standout was rookie running back JaMycal Hasty, who "was enjoyable to watch as he jitterbugged down the field on each of his three carries."

https://t.co/pNerWb0gQf

name: sfchronicle
text: Update: California energy grid managers said they do not expect more rolling blackouts Saturday, even after PG&E warned that additional outages could be required. https://t.co/M4fzsvmvrT

name: sfchronicle
text:
“I can just go out there and play football and run through someone’s face." 

After signing a five-year extension that made 49ers tight end George Kittle the NFL’s highest-paid player at his position, he discussed how the money provided security.

https://t.co/DzJjq0Vpif

name: sfchronicle
text:
BREAKING: PG&E blacks out power to 220,000 customers Saturday night in the second day of outages amid a heat wave that continues to strain the state's energy grid. 

Affected homes and businesses are in parts of the Central Coast and Central Valley. https://t.co/ZAw2LuV4s3

name: sfchronicle
text:
Down to their last strike at Oracle Park, the A’s did their thing again, as Mark Canha whacked a last-second homer to give Oakland the win over the Giants, 7-6. The A’s improved to a league best 15-6. 

@SusanSlusser has the latest: https://t.co/orjC7OzszL

name: sfchronicle
text:
In a frightful rerun, the Giants incomprehensibly gave up a three-run advantage and lost 7-6 to the A's on Saturday. With the same pitcher on the mound, giving it up the same way, with another defensive mistake making it possible.

Story by @HankSchulman: https://t.co/xtHK1LntjS

name: sfchronicle
text:
Matt Olson is a home-run hitter. Recently, he has been only a home-run hitter.

Story by @MatthewKawahara: https://t.co/WaxGRoLe8t

name: sfchronicle
text:
As the Loyalton Fire, north of Tahoe, grew amid extreme heat and intense winds, it sent up a tall column of smoke that appears to have formed into a fire-fueled tornado — similar to the one seen during the 2018 Carr Fire in Redding.

https://t.co/Suiow1cx6h

name: sfchronicle
text:
Update: PG&E says it has restored electricity to most customers affected by rolling outages in the Central Coast and Central Valley. The outages, prompted by a massive heatwave straining the state's energy grid, lasted around three hours. 

https://t.co/ecmuxHjd65

name: sfchronicle
text:
The A's are 15-6, looking solid in first place ahead of the Houston Astros’ three-ring circus, writes columnist @Bruce_Jenkins1.

Who’s to say Oakland can’t win the championship if the postseason is actually played? 

https://t.co/PQzexx5q0o
